Ensure that the following packages are installed and loaded:twitteR, rtweet, dplyr, tidyr

Environment Set Up

Information needed to pull data from twitter: CONSUMER_KEY, CONSUMER SECRET,ACCESS_TOKEN, ACCESS_SECRET. This willl vary based on your own twitter account.

Creates the authetication to the twitter API, without a valid authentication the twitter pulls will fail.

setup_twitter_oauth(consumer_key, consumer_secret, access_token, access_secret)
## [1] "Using direct authentication"

Set Up Path. Ensure to change the variable myPath with your own path accordingly.

Pulls Data from Twitter based on specified keywords or hashtags, specifying how many tweets to pull, in both english and spanish, and saves each pull into a variable. Things to note: Twitter limits the amount of pulls one can do within 15 minutes.

tweets3000_daily <- searchTwitter("Venezuela OR #Venezuela OR Maduro OR #Maduro", n = 3000, retryOnRateLimit = 120 )

Convert the pulled tweets, which are class type list, from the previous step into a Data Frame in order to analyze the data.

tweets.df3000 <- twListToDF(tweets3000_daily)

We need to add a column to each data frame that adds the date the tweet was pulled. We store this in a new variable so we wont edit the source.

tweets.df3000.ec <- mutate(tweets.df3000,source_data=date())

Append the recently pulled data with the previously loaded data.

test_upd <- rbind(test,tweets.df3000.ec)

Quickly analyze the newly appended data frame

Cleaning the Data

Looking at the StatusSource variable, it has the following format:

head(select(test_rmv_dups,statusSource),5)
##                                                                           statusSource
## 1 <a href="http://twitter.com/download/android" rel="nofollow">Twitter for Android</a>
## 2                 <a href="https://mobile.twitter.com" rel="nofollow">Twitter Lite</a>
## 3                  <a href="http://publicize.wp.com/" rel="nofollow">WordPress.com</a>
## 4                   <a href="http://twitter.com" rel="nofollow">Twitter Web Client</a>

Seperate statusSource based on the sep > in order to see the platform of the Tweet (Android, Iphone, Ipad)

test_rmv_dups_sep <- separate(test_rmv_dups,statusSource, c("URL","Platform"),sep=">")
## Warning: Expected 2 pieces. Additional pieces discarded in 188898 rows [1,

Manipulating the Data

Create a DF with only the Platform used

commonPlatform <- select(test_rmv_dups_sep2,Platform)

Create a variable that holds the frequency of the common platforms used Source: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/24576515/relative-frequencies-proportions-with-dplyr/24576703

commonPlatform_freq <- summarize(group_by(commonPlatform,Platform),freq=n())

Arrange the common platform in descending order, to see which type of device/platform was most used.

commonPlatform_freq_desc <- arrange(commonPlatform_freq, desc(freq))

MCRC_ts <- filter(test_rmv_dups_sep2, screenName=="MCRC_Venezuela" | screenName=="NoticiasVenezue")

Line Graph showing the number of tweets of the top 2 users, using qplot

qplot(created, data = MCRC_ts, geom="freqpoly", colour = screenName)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

ggplot(MCRC_ts, aes(x=created,colour=screenName))+geom_freqpoly()+labs(title= "Time Analysis", subtitle="Top two users",x="Date", y="# of Tweets", caption="Source: Twitter Data with Maduro or #Maduro or Venezuela or #Venezuela")

Creating a Pie Chart of all Platforms >1% First we need to aggragate all the Platforms that are under 1% into an Other Category

df1 <- filter(commonPlatform_prop, prop>1)
df2 <- filter(commonPlatform_prop, prop<1)
sumfreq <- sum(df2$freq)
sumprop <- sum(df2$prop)
df3 <- data.frame(Platform='Other',freq = sumfreq, prop=sumprop)
df4 <- rbind(df1,df3)

Confirm that the prop of df4 = 100

df4

Creating first a bar chart. Source: http://www.sthda.com/english/wiki/ggplot2-pie-chart-quick-start-guide-r-software-and-data-visualization

platformBar<- ggplot(df4, aes(x="", y=df4$prop, fill=df4$Platform))+ geom_bar(width = 1, stat = "identity")
platformBar

Create the pie chart. Source: http://www.sthda.com/english/wiki/ggplot2-pie-chart-quick-start-guide-r-software-and-data-visualization

platformPie <- platformBar + coord_polar("y", start=0) 
platformPie + labs(title= "Platforms from Twitter",y="Proportion", fill="Platform", caption="Source: Twitter Data with Maduro or #Maduro or Venezuela or #Venezuela")

Creates a Dot Plot, showing the number of tweets by platform

ggplot(arrange(df4,df4$freq), aes(x = freq, y = Platform, fill=Platform)) + geom_dotplot(binaxis = "y", stackgroups = FALSE, binwidth = .2, method = "histodot") + labs(title= "# of Tweets by Platform",y="Proportion", x="# of Tweets", fill="Platform", caption="Source: Twitter Data with Maduro or #Maduro or Venezuela or #Venezuela")

Tweet Geo-location Analysis

We want to find out the location of the tweets based on the latitude and longtiude variables/columns. We removed the NAs using the drop_na tidyr function. Source: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/4862178/remove-rows-with-nas-missing-values-in-data-frame
Another way to accomplish this task is to use the following dplyr filter function: test_lat_long <- filter(test_lat_long_1, !is.na(latitude), !is.na(longitude))

test_lat_long1 <- drop_na(test_rmv_dups_sep2, latitude, longitude)

Create a variable that holds the frequency of the geographic data, and arranges it by descending order.

lat_long_freq <- arrange(summarize(group_by(test_lat_long1,longitude,latitude),freq=n()),desc(freq))

Combining ggmap and ggplot we can overlay data points on the map. We are limited based on the zoom level specified in the previous line of code.

ggmap(ven_map) + geom_point(aes(x = longitude, y = latitude), colour = "red", alpha = 0.1, size = 5, data = lat_long_freq)
## Warning: Removed 4 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

For a more interactive map. We can use the leaflet plugin. Source: https://rstudio.github.io/leaflet/ We can overlay points based on the lat and long variables. We can also add an interactive label which shows the frequency

m <- leaflet(lat_long_freq) %>% addTiles%>%
  addProviderTiles(providers$OpenStreetMap) %>%
  addCircles(lng = ~longitude, lat = ~latitude, radius=~freq*10, opacity=1, col="blue",  label=~as.character(freq), labelOptions = labelOptions(textsize = "14px"))

m

The leaflet.extra library expands the leaflet functionality, allowing us to create heatmaps. We can overlay our previous layer where we added the circles, onto the heatmap, as well as adding interactive labels In this case hovering over the dots, will show the number of tweets coming from that location

m <- leaflet(lat_long_freq) %>% addTiles%>%
  addProviderTiles(providers$OpenStreetMap) %>%
  addWebGLHeatmap(lng=~longitude, lat=~latitude, intensity = ~freq, size= 20, units = 'px') %>%
  addCircles(lng = ~longitude, lat = ~latitude, radius=~freq*10, opacity=1, col="blue",  label=~as.character(freq), labelOptions = labelOptions(textsize = "14px"))
m

Leaflet also allows us to create Circle Markers, the difference of adding Circles and Circle Markers is that the radius when using CircleMarkers, remains the same. Also, Circlemarkers give us the ability to automatically cluster our data based on zoom level, using markerClusterOption Using the original lat_long_1 data frame, which contains all the information from twitter. label=c(as.character(screenName),as.Date(created))

test_lat_long1$longitude <- as.numeric(as.character(test_lat_long1$longitude))
test_lat_long1$latitude <- as.numeric(as.character(test_lat_long1$latitude))
m <- leaflet(test_lat_long1) %>% addTiles%>%
  addProviderTiles(providers$OpenStreetMap) %>%
  addCircleMarkers(lng = ~longitude, lat = ~latitude, radius=10, opacity=1, col="blue",  label=(~screenName),labelOptions = labelOptions(textsize = "14px"),clusterOptions = markerClusterOptions())
m
